  "content": "üß† Teaching AI When to Say ‚ÄúI Don‚Äôt Know‚Äù - a Next Step in Building Trustworthy Systemsüßê One of the biggest risks with today‚Äôs AI systems is not what they do not know, it is that they do not know what they do not know‚ö° Even worse, they often make things up with confidence (and we often do not know betterüòî)üìÑ A new paper titled ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt lie to your friends: Learning what you know from collaborative self-play‚Äù from a team from Google DeepMind introduces a promising training method to fix this by teaching AI agents how to collaborate, admit uncertainty, and know when to ask for help.üîç Here‚Äôs what the authors propose:üëâ Collaborative Self-Play: Multiple AI agents, each with access to different tools or knowledge sources, are trained to work together to answer factual questions. The hopeful outcome? They learn to: üëâ Recognise the limits of their own knowledgeüëâ Communicate uncertaintyüëâ Use tools in a more sensible wayüëâ Ask (others) for inputüí∞Rewarding humility, not just accuracy: Instead of penalizing ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know,‚Äù the system rewards agents that seek support or signal uncertainty ‚Äî a step toward real AI reliability.üìà Why this matters for AI governance:‚ö†Ô∏è Hallucinations remain one of the biggest trust issues in GenAI‚úÖ Collaborative Self-Play is intended to lead to agents that are more self-aware and cautious in their answersüß© This might support a central goal of frameworks like the EU AI Act: AI that‚Äôs not only powerful but honest, interpretable, and saferüìçIn any case, AI that knows when it is out of its depth would be a great step forward in developing trustworthy explainable AI applications where risk are better manageableüîó to the paper in the commentshashtag#artificialintelligence hashtag#innovation hashtag#future hashtag#governance hashtag#compliance",
